<title>LUXEMBOURG: EU Court upholds Unilever, Argos VAT refund case.</title>
<headline>EU Court upholds Unilever, Argos VAT refund case.</headline>
<dateline>LUXEMBOURG 1996-10-24</dateline>
<text>
<p>The European Court upheld on Thursday a move by Unilever subsidiary Elida Faberge and retail chain Argos to have the British government pay back excess VAT paid on discounted goods.</p>
<p>The court said in such cases VAT was payable on the discounted and not the full price, a decision that could require substantial repayments to companies from the British government.  </p>
<p>Interpreting an EU law on the harmonisation of taxes, the court said that &quot;the taxable amount (of a product) is equal to the selling price charged by the manufacturer, less the amount indicated on the voucher and refunded.&quot;</p>
<p>According to court documents, Unilever asked the British government to repay 883,894 pounds ($1.4 million). Argos asked for 1.4 million pounds.</p>
<p>Some industry reports, however, have suggested that such a ruling could win the plaintiffs and other British companies a payback of as much as 400 million pounds. $= 1.59 pounds</p>
